      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Judges often operate on ingrained biases, and they tend to equate stability with moral fiber. An unstable employment history in an urban setting is often subconsciously coded as irresponsibility or a failure to adhere to societal norms, which they interpret as a lack of discipline. They may view the challenges of an underserved environment not as systemic failures, but as personal failings that the individual has chosen to succumb to. This bias allows them to frame socioeconomic disadvantage as a character flaw rather than a structural problem.",
